prompts/ defines the LLM prompt files that drive the codebase-summarization pipeline itself: leaf summarization, rollup summarization, and auditing. Nothing here is executable code — these are system prompts loaded verbatim by runner code, and the directory's contract is that all task-specific dynamic data (file paths, diffs, directory contents) stays out of these files and lives only in the runner's user-message construction.

The three prompts form a linear pipeline with strict output-format coupling: summarizer-leaf.md produces per-file `.ctx` docs, summarizer-rollup.md consumes those `.ctx` files plus subdirectory `rollup.ctx` files (never re-deriving from source) to produce a directory-level `rollup.ctx`, and auditor.md consumes `intent.md` + `rollup.ctx` to emit a JSON verdict. A change to the rollup's `intent_divergence:` label format must be mirrored in auditor.md, which greps for that exact signal. Changing the `.ctx` schema or tone in summarizer-leaf.md likewise requires checking summarizer-rollup.md for consistency, since a rollup sits alongside sibling leaf `.ctx` files at the same chain level.

Both summarizer prompts share an anti-duplication discipline (facts stated once, banned filler phrases, present-tense/no-history) and a "facts only, no hedging" ethos that auditor.md extends into strict JSON-only output with a fixed enum (severity "none" only for "consistent" verdicts). README.md documents the meta-contract binding all three: prompts are portable across model upgrades, contain no embedded runner logic, and any meaningful edit to a prompt file requires re-running the existing summary tree so outputs match the new standard — there is no versioning inside these files, only git history.